    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 2.5",
    "body" : "<p>Just use <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/util/ArrayList.html#contains%28java.lang.Object%29\" rel=\"noreferrer\">ArrayList.contains(desiredElement)</a>.  For example, if you're looking for the conta1 account from your example, you could use something like:</p>\n\n<pre><code>if (lista.contains(conta1)) {\n    System.out.println(\"Account found\");\n} else {\n    System.out.println(\"Account not found\");\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>Edit:</strong>\nNote that in order for this to work, you will need to properly override the <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/Object.html#equals(java.lang.Object)\" rel=\"noreferrer\">equals()</a> and <a href=\"http://download.oracle.com/javase/6/docs/api/java/lang/Object.html#hashCode()\" rel=\"noreferrer\">hashCode()</a> methods. If you are using Eclipse IDE, then you can have these methods generated by first opening the source file for your <code>CurrentAccount</code> object and the selecting <code>Source &gt; Generate hashCode() and equals()...</code></p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "account_id" : 682929,
      "reputation" : 569,
      "user_id" : 537375,
      "user_type" : "unregistered",
      "profile_image" : "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/d24ce3d19ef001a24f77a42fb51cbf22?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
      "display_name" : "SBA",
      "link" : "https://stackoverflow.com/users/537375/sba"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
